replies.bodyText:
try (HttpURLConnection con = new URL(...); BufferReader in = new BufferedReader(...))
{ ... }
catch (...) { ... }
finally
{
    in.close();
}

The benefit is not the fancy braces, but the assurance that the finally block will always run and close the resource(s) if any exception (caught or uncaught) is triggered.
In fact, another benefit is that you don't even need to write the finally, when you use try with resources, it automatically closes all the resources for you in a magic finally block, thanks Java.

